==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|-te|pos=preterite ending}}, {{m|enm|-t|pos=past participle ending}}, from {{inh|en|ang|-te}}, {{m|ang|-de|pos=first and third person preterite ending}}, {{m|ang|-t}}, {{m|ang|-d|pos=past participle ending}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*-id-|pos=preterite stem ending of class 1 weak verbs}} and {{m|gem-pro|*-idaz|pos=past participle ending of class 1 weak verbs}}.

In some verbs, like {{m|en|lose}}/{{m|en|lost}}, the ''-t-/-t'' was merely an alteration of earlier ''-d-/-d'' during the Middle English period. See {{m|en|-ed}}.

====Suffix====
{{en-suffix|cat2=inflectional suffixes}}

# Forms the past tense and/or past participle of some verbs (leapt, kept, dreamt, blest, etc.)

=====Usage notes=====
Some verbs have both an [[-ed]] and a [[-t]] form. The '''-t''' form has become [[obsolete]] for many verbs, e.g. [[toucht]].

Usually for verbs with "eep" or "end" at the end (e.g. [[kept]] for [[keep]], [[slept]] for [[sleep]], [[wept]] for [[weep]], [[bent]] for [[bend]], [[sent]] for [[send]], [[went]] for [[wend]]). More rarely, for nasals (e.g. [[burnt]] for [[burn]], [[dreamt]] for [[dream]]).

