====Letter====
{{head|ar|letter|tr=-}}{{LR}} ({{l|ar|تَاء مَرْبُوطَة}})

# {{n-g|{{l|ar|ة|tr=tāʾ marbūṭa}} is a variant of the letter {{l|ar|ت|tr=tāʾ}} used at the end of words. It is formed from the letter {{l|ar|ه|tr=hāʾ}} with the addition of the two overdots of {{l|ar|ت|tr=tāʾ}}.}}

=====Usage notes=====
* It mostly exists in grammatically feminine words. It always follows a [[fatḥa]] <big>{{m|ar|ـَ|tr=-}}</big> ("a"), and it is replaced with a normal {{m|ar|ت|tr=tāʾ}} when a suffix is added, e.g. {{m|ar|غُرْفَة|gloss=a room}} -> {{m|ar||غُرْفَتِي|gloss=my room}} ({{m|ar|غُرْفَة}}{{LR}} ({{lang|ar|ة}}{{LR}} -> {{m|ar|ت|tr=-}}{{LR}}) + {{m|ar|ـِي}}{{LR}}).
* When [[desinential inflection]] is used in Classical Arabic or in formal Modern Standard Arabic, non-pausal {{m|ar|ة|tr=-}} is pronounced as {{IPAchar|/t/}} (preceded by usually unwritten fatḥa "a") and has -u/un, -i/-in, -a/an case endings, e.g. {{m|ar|لُغَةٌ|tr=-}} - "luḡah" (pausal), "luḡa''tun''" formal, non-pausal pronunciation ([[nominative case]], indefinite).
* Adverbials from ''tāʾ marbūṭa'' do not add alif ({{m|ar|ا}}) with fatḥatān. Instead, fatḥatān is attached directly to tāʾ marbūṭa and the "hidden t" is pronounced with the ending "-an" e .g. {{m|ar|عَادَةً|gloss=usually}}.
* In a more relaxed orthography {{m|ar|ة|tr=-}} is replaced with {{m|ar|ه|tr=hāʾ}} with the same pronunciation, especially in Egypt and Sudan.
* Loanwords in other languages (e.g. {{cog|fa|-}} or {{cog|tr|-}}) from words with ''tāʾ marbūṭa'' use the endings ''at'', ''et'', ''ah'', ''a'' or ''e''.

