===Etymology 1===
Probably from {{der|en|gml|pūs}}, {{m|gml|pūskatte}} or {{der|en|nl|poes||puss, cat”, slang for “vulva}}, ultimately from a common {{der|en|gem}} word for cat, perhaps ultimately {{onomatopoeic|en|title=imitative}} of a sound made to get its attention (compare Arabic [[بسة]] (bissa)).

Akin to {{cog|fy|poes}}, {{cog|nds|Puus}}, {{m|nds|Puuskatte}}, {{cog|da|pus}}, dialectal {{cog|sv|kattepus}}, {{cog|no|pus}}.

Found also in several other European, North African and West Asian languages; compare {{cog|ro|pisică}} and {{cog|sc|pisittu}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|informal|often as a term of address}} A [[cat]].
#: {{ux|en|Our local theatre is showing '''Puss''' in Boots.}}
#: {{ux|en|Come here, '''puss'''! I've got some milk for you.}}
# {{lb|en|dated|affectionate}} A [[girl]] or young [[woman]], or any [[child]].
# {{lb|en|dated|hunting}} A [[hare]].
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones}}
#*: He then began to beat about, in the same language and in the same manner as if he had been beating for a hare; and at last cried out, "Soho! '''Puss''' is not far off. Here's her form, upon my soul; I believe I may cry stole away."
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1886|translator=H.L. Br&aelig;kstad|author=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|authorlink=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|title=Folk and Fairy Tales|page=77|passage='It won't kill '''Puss''' any better for that.' 'But, goodness gracious, what can that hare be made of?' I asked.}}
# {{lb|en|vulgar|slang}} The [[vulva]] (female [[genitalia]]).
# {{lb|en|vulgar|slang|metonymic}} [[sex|Sex]] with a woman.
# {{lb|en|vulgar|slang|chiefly|_|North America}} A [[coward]]; a [[wuss]]; someone who is unable to stand up for themself.

