==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|-ick}} {{qualifier|obsolete}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*-kos}}
From {{inh|en|enm|-ik}}, from {{der|en|fro|-ique}}, from {{der|en|la|-icus}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|[[*-kos|*-kos, *-ḱos]]}}, formed with the [[Appendix:Glossary#i-stem|i-stem]] suffix {{m|ine-pro|*-i-}} and the adjectival suffix {{m|ine-pro|[[*-kos|*-kos, *-ḱos]]}}. Compare {{cog|grc|-ικός}}, {{cog|sa|-इक}} and {{cog|cu|-ъкъ}}. {{doublet|en|-y}}.

PIE {{m|ine-pro|*-kos}} on noun stems carried the meaning 'characteristic of, like, typical, pertaining to', and on adjectival stems it acted emphatically.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|en|/ɪk/}}

===Suffix===
{{en-suffix|cat2=adjective-forming suffixes|cat3=productive suffixes}}

# {{n-g|Used to form adjectives from nouns with the meaning “of or pertaining to”.}}
#: {{m|en|Cyrillic}}
#: {{m|en|acidic}}
# {{lb|en|chemistry}} {{n-g|Used to denote certain [[chemical compound]]s in which a specified [[chemical element]] has a higher [[oxidation number]] than in the equivalent compound whose name ends in the suffix {{m|en|-ous}}. For example [[sulphuric acid]] ([[hydrogen|H]]₂[[sulfate|SO₄]]) has more oxygen atoms per molecule than [[sulphurous acid]] (H₂[[sulfite|SO₃]]).}}

====Usage notes====
The suffix {{m|en|-ic}} is often added to words of Greek or Latin origin, but may also be used with other words, and in some cases is even added (redundantly) to adjectives, as in {{m|en|veganic}} (from {{m|en|vegan}}).

