===Etymology===
From {{bor|eu|la|-tus|-tum}}, a past participle forming suffix. Basque borrowed Latin verbs in their participle form (for example, {{m|eu|aditu|t=to hear}} from {{m|la|audītum}}, neuter perfect passive participle of {{m|la|audiō|t=I hear}}), with the ending being reinterpreted as a new verb forming suffix.<ref>{{R:EDB|350}}</ref>

===Suffix===
{{eu-suffix}}

# {{non-gloss definition|A verb-forming suffix.}}
#: {{suffixusex|eu|euskara|t1=Basque|euskaratu|t2=to translate into Basque}}
#: {{suffixusex|eu|ohera|t1=to, towards bed|oheratu|t2=to go to bed}}
#: {{suffixusex|eu|gehi|t1=plus|gehitu|t2=to add}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to form [[adjective]]s, roughly corresponding to the English past participle forming suffix}} {{m|en|-ed}}.
#: {{suffixusex|eu|gehi|t1=plus|gehitu|t2=augmented}}

====Usage notes====
* Takes the form {{m|eu|-du}} after words ending in {{IPAchar|/l/}} or {{IPAchar|/n/}}:
*: {{suffixusex|eu|lagun|lagundu|t1=friend|t2=to help}}
* This is the only productive verb-forming suffix in modern Basque, having displaced the native suffix {{m|eu|-i}}.
* Verbs taking this suffix have no synthetic forms (with the exception of {{m|eu|ezagutu|t=to know}}).

