==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/tiːm/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-team.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|iːm|s=1}}
* {{homophones|en|teem}}

===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dewk-}}
From {{der|en|enm|teme}}, from {{der|en|ang|tēam||child-bearing, offspring, [[brood]], set of draught animals}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*taumaz||that which draws or pulls}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*taugijaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*tugōną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*teuhōną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*teuhaną||to lead, bring, pull, draw}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*dewk-||to pull, lead}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|team}}, {{m|sco|teem||a chain, harness}}, {{cog|fy|team||bridle, team}}, {{cog|nl|toom||bridle, reins, flock of birds}}, {{cog|de|Zaum||bridle}}, {{cog|no|tømme||bridle, rein}}, {{cog|sv|töm||leash, rein}}. More at {{l|en|teem}}, {{l|en|tie}}, {{l|en|tow}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A set of [[draught animal]]s, such as two horses in front of a [[carriage]].
#* {{RQ:Macaulay History of England|chapter=3|passage=It happened almost every day that coaches stuck fast, until a '''team''' of cattle could be procured from some neighbouring farm to tug them out of the slough.}}
#* '''1931''', {{w|William Faulkner}}, ''[[w:Sanctuary (Faulkner novel)|Sanctuary]]'', Vintage 1993, page 111:
#*: The adjacent alleys were choked with tethered wagons, the '''teams''' reversed and nuzzling gnawed corn-ears over the tail-boards.
# Any [[group]] of [[people]] involved in the same activity, especially [[sports]] or [[work]].
#: {{ux|en|We need more volunteers for the netball '''team'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|The IT manager leads a '''team''' of three software developers.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A group of animals moving together, especially young ducks.
#* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World}}
#*: she will wonder to have a '''teeme''' of ducklings about her
#* {{RQ:Dryden Virgil|Aeneis}}
#*: a long '''team''' of snowy swans on high
# {{lb|en|UK|legal|obsolete}} A royalty or privilege granted by royal charter to a lord of a manor, of having, keeping, and judging in his court, his bondmen, neifes, and villains, and their offspring, or suit, that is, goods and chattels, and appurtenances thereto.
#* '''1871''', Alexander M. Burrill, ''Law Dictioary & Glossary'', vol II, [http://www.archive.org/details/cu31924022836450]
#*: TEAM, Theam, Tem, Them. Sax. [from tyman, to propagate, to teem.] In old English law. Literally, an offspring, race or generation. A royalty or privilege granted by royal charter to a lord of a manor, of having, keeping and judging in his court, his bondmen, neifes and villeins, and their offspring or suit. They who had a jurisdiction of this kind, were said to have a court of Theme... constantly used in the old books in connection with toll, in the expression Toll & Team.
# A group of people who favor one side of a binary debate that is divided and lacks a well-established clear consensus.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 27, 2019
|author=Bill Chappell
|title=People Can't Even Agree On When The Decade Ends
|work=NPR
|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/27/791546842/people-cant-even-agree-on-when-the-decade-ends
|page=
|passage=As Jan. 1, 2020, approaches, it turns out there is a '''Team''' Zero and a Team 1 – those who believe the new decade will begin after midnight on the upcoming New Year's Eve and those who believe the burgeoning celebrations of a new decade (and all the "last decade" retrospectives) are in fact a year early.}}

=====Usage notes=====
* In British English, ''team'' is [[construe]]d as plural, emphasizing the members. In US English it is construed as singular, emphasizing the group. This conforms to the general practice in the two dialects for [[collective noun]]s.
** British English: {{quote-book|en|title=Building the Team| page=124| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1136424261| author={{w|Institute of Leadership & Management}}| year=2012| passage=At the storming stage, the '''team are''' trying to establish relationships with one another, and to determine who will take the dominant roles.}}
** American English: {{quote-book|en|title=Team Building: Proven Strategies for Improving Team Performance| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118047443| author={{w|William G. Dyer}}, W. Gibb Dyer, Jr., Jeffrey H. Dyer| year=2010| passage=When a subordinate wants to give feedback to a boss, this is typically only done in a roundabout way through the “grapevine” (other members of the team), usually when the '''team is''' out at night drinking.}}

