==Latin==

===Etymology===
{{root|la|ine-pro|*dʰeh₁-}}
From {{inh|la|itc-pro|*fakjō}}, from {{inh|la|ine-pro|*dʰeh₁-||to put, place, set}}, possibly through a later intermediate root {{m|ine-pro|*dʰh₁-k-yé/ó-}}. Cognates include {{cog|grc|τίθημι}}, {{cog|sa|दधाति|tr=dádhāti}}, {{cog|ang|dōn}} (English {{m|en|do}}) and Lithuanian {{m|lt|dėti||to put}}.

The passive voice is [[suppletive]]ly provided by the unrelated verb {{m|la|fīō||I become, I am made}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-IPA|faciō|eccl=yes}}
* {{audio|la|la-cls-facio.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}

===Verb===
{{la-verb|irreg|faciō}}

# I [[do]] (particularly as a [[specific]] [[instance]] or [[occasion]] of doing)
#: {{ux|la|Quid '''feci'''?|What '''have''' I '''done'''?}}
#: {{ux|la|Latrocinium modo '''factum est'''.|A robbery just '''took place'''.|q=special usage''; passive perfect = took place, lit. has been made/is done''}}
#: {{ux|la|'''Factum''' est.|''(It)'' is '''done'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Cicero Catiline}}
#*: {{ux|la|Quam diu quisquam erit qui te defendere audeat, vives, et vives ita ut nunc vivis, multis meis et firmis praesidiis obsessus ne commovere te contra rem publicam possis. Multorum te etiam oculi et aures non sentientem, sicut adhuc '''fecerunt''', speculabuntur atque custodient.|As long as one person exists who can dare to defend you, you shall live; but you shall live as you do now, surrounded by my many and trusty guards, so that you shall not be able to stir one finger against the republic: many eyes and ears shall still observe and watch you, as they have hitherto '''done''', though you shall not perceive them.}}
# I [[make]], [[construct]], [[fashion]], [[frame]], [[build]], [[erect]]
# I [[make]], [[produce]], [[compose]].
#* {{Q|la|Jerome|Vulgate|Genesis|1|3|quote=dixitque Deus '''fiat''' lux et '''facta''' est lux|trans=And God said: Let light be '''made'''. And light was '''made'''.}}
# I [[appoint]].

====Conjugation====
{{la-conj|irreg.sigmpasv|faciō}}

;Passive: If one were to follow the Proto-Italic verb {{m|itc-pro|*fakiō|*fakiō, *fakiesi}}, the passive would be ''facior'', ''facī'' in the present. However, these forms are not attested before or during the Classical period.

====Usage notes====
''Facere'' renders a sense of doing or making with respect to a specific instance of so doing or making; for more continuative senses of doing or making, compare {{l|la|ago}}, {{l|la|agito}} and {{l|la|gero}}. In [[Late Latin|Late]] and [[Medieval Latin]] the verb was used with infinitives to form causative constructions (e.g. cf. {{m|en|fieri facias}}), which are a calque from (Proto-)Romance considered inappropriate in [[Classical Latin]].

