===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|dadd}}, {{m|enm|dadde}}, of uncertain origin.

* Perhaps {{onomatopoeic|en|title=imitative}} of a child's first uttered syllables {{m|und||da}}, {{m|und||da}}.<ref>{{R:OED}}</ref>
* Possibly related to {{cog|nds|detta||grandfather}}.<ref>[http://www.dbnl.org/arch/scho075woor01_01/pag/scho075woor01_01.pdf#page=39 Schönfeld Wichers, K.D. (1959). "Woordenboek Rijssens Dialect." p.19.]</ref>
* Possibly from a metathetic variation of unrecorded {{cog|ang|*ætta}}, {{m|ang|*atta||father}}, from {{cog|gem-pro|*attô}} {{gloss|"father, forefather"; whence also {{cog|frr|ate}}, {{m|frr|aatj}}, {{m|frr|taatje}}, {{m|frr|tääte|t=father; dad}}, {{cog|de|Tate|t=dad}}, {{cog|bar|tatte|t=dad}}, {{cog|cim|tatta|t=dad}}, {{cog|no|taate|t=dad}}, {{cog|is|táta|t=dad}}}}, from {{cog|ine-pro|*átta|t=father}}, whence {{cog|sa|तत|t=father}}.
* Or, perhaps of {{der|en|cel}} origin, compare {{cog|cy|-}} and {{cog|br|tad}} (from {{der|en|cel-bry-pro|*tad}}), {{cog|sga|data}}; and possibly related to {{cog|ru|дя́дя||uncle}} and/or {{cog|ru|де́душка||grandfather}}, all imitative.

