===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Someone who watches over something; a person in charge of something or someone.
#: {{ux|en|The camp '''monitors''' look after the children during the night, when the teachers are asleep.}}
#* '''1829''', Charles Sprague, ''[[s:To My Cigar|To My Cigar]]''
#*: And oft, mild friend, to me thou art
#*: A '''monitor''', though still;
#*: Thou speak'st a lesson to my heart,
#*: Beyond the preacher's skill.
# A device that detects and informs on the presence, quantity, etc., of something.
# {{lb|en|computing}} A device similar to a [[television set]] used as to give a graphical display of the output from a [[computer]].
#: {{ux|en|The information flashed up on the '''monitor'''.}}
# A [[studio monitor]] or [[loudspeaker]].
# {{lb|en|computing}} A [[program]] for viewing and editing.
#: {{ux|en|a machine code '''monitor'''}}
# {{lb|en|British|archaic}} A student leader in a class.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1871|author=[[s:Henry William Pullen|Henry William Pullen]]| title=[[s:The Fight at Dame Europa's School|The Fight at Dame Europa's School]]| passage=So, as she did not like the masters to be prying about the play-ground out of school, she chose from among the biggest and most trustworthy of her pupils five '''monitors''', who had authority over the rest of the Boys, and kept the unruly ones in order.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1881|author={{w|Talbot Baines Reed}}| title=[[s:The Fifth Form at St. Dominic's/Chapter X|The Fifth Form at St. Dominic's]]| chapter=X| passage=But it was not so—at least, not always—for though they fell out among themselves, they united their forces against the common enemy—the '''monitors'''!}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} One of a class of relatively small [[armored]] [[warship|warships]] with only one or two [[turret]]s (but often carrying unusually large [[gun]]s for a warship of its size), designed for [[shore]] [[bombardment]] or [[riverine]] [[warfare]] rather than [[combat]] with other ships.
# {{lb|en|archaic}} An [[ironclad]].
# A [[monitor lizard]].
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} One who admonishes; one who warns of faults, informs of duty, or gives advice and instruction by way of reproof or caution.
#* {{RQ:Bacon Villiers}}
#*: You need not be a '''monitor''' to your gracious master the king.
#* '''1873''', ''Gardeners Chronicle & New Horticulturist'' (page 119)
#*: There has been no lack of other '''monitors''' — a ticklish [[haysel]], a flooded harvest all through the north {{...}}
# {{lb|en|engineering}} A tool holder, as for a lathe, shaped like a low turret, and capable of being revolved on a vertical pivot so as to bring the several tools successively into position.
# A [[monitor nozzle]].

