===Etymology 2===
Formed in English by [[conversion]] ([[anthimeria]]) of the transitive verb {{m|en|leave#Etymology 1|t=cause or allow to remain available}}. Attested since the 19th century, with earliest references to billiards.<ref>{{R:OED Online|leave|n.{{sup|2}}|106778|September, 2016}}</ref>

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|cricket}} The action of the [[batsman]] not attempting to play at the ball.
# {{lb|en|billiards}} The arrangement of balls in play that remains after a shot is made (which determines whether the next shooter — who may be either the same player, or an opponent — has good options, or only poor ones).
#* {{quote-journal|en|1890||Slosson’s Close Shave|{{w|New York Times}}|||Having counted 38 points he tried a beautiful [[massé]] out of the corner, hit the first ball just a trifle too hard and kissed his own ball off just when victory seemed to be his. The '''leave''' was unfortunate for Ives. Slosson played brilliantly and ran the game out, a close winner, with 22 points.|month=February 27|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00A17FF3E5F10738DDDAE0A94DA405B8085F0D3}}

===Etymology 3===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*lewbʰ-|id=love}}
From {{inh|en|enm|leve}}, from {{inh|en|ang|lēaf||permission, privilege}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*laubō}}, {{m|gem-pro|*laubą||permission, privilege, favour, worth}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*lewbʰ-||to love, hold dear}}. Cognate with obsolete {{cog|de|Laube||permission}}, {{cog|sv|lov||permission}}, {{cog|is|leyfi||permission}}. Related to {{cog|nl|verlof}}, {{cog|de|Erlaubnis}}. See also {{l|en|love}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|holiday}} Permission to be absent; [[time]] away from one's [[work]].
#: {{syn|en|annual leave|holiday|Thesaurus:vacation}}
#: {{ux|en|I've been given three weeks' '''leave''' by my boss.}}
# {{senseid|en|permission}}{{lb|en|dated|or|legal}} [[permission|Permission]].
#: {{syn|en|authorisation|consent}}
#: {{ux|en|Might I beg '''leave''' to accompany you?}}
#: {{ux|en|The applicant now seeks '''leave''' to appeal and, if '''leave''' be granted, to appeal against these sentences.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|act=III|scene=ii|passage=Since I have your good '''leave''' to go away, / I will make haste: but, till I come again, / No bed shall e'er be guilty of my stay, / Nor rest be interposer 'twixt us twain.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} [[farewell|Farewell]], [[departure]].
#: {{ux|en|I took my '''leave''' of the gentleman without a backward glance.}}

