#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|J.R.R. Tolkien}}|title={{w|The Fellowship of the Ring}}|chapter=I: A Long-Expected Party|series={{w|The Lord of the Rings}}|isbn=9780345339706|date=29 July 1954|seriesvolume=1|passage= The '''flowers''' glowed red and golden: snapdragons and sunflowers, and nasturtians trailing all over the turf walls and peeping in at the round windows. }}
# {{lb|en|botany}} A [[reproductive]] structure in [[angiosperm]]s (flowering plants), often conspicuously colourful and typically including [[sepal]]s, [[petal]]s, and either or both [[stamen]]s and/or a [[pistil]].
#* '''1894''', {{w|H. G. Wells}}, ''[[s:The Flowering of the Strange Orchid|The Flowering of the Strange Orchid]]''
#*: You know, Darwin studied their fertilisation, and showed that the whole structure of an ordinary orchid '''flower''' was contrived in order that moths might carry the pollen from plant to plant.
# A [[plant]] that bears flowers, especially a plant that is small and lacks [[wood]].
#: {{ux|en|We transplanted the '''flowers''' to a larger pot.}}
# {{lb|en|usually with [[in]]}} Of plants, a state of bearing [[bloom]]s.
#: {{ux|en|The dogwoods are in '''flower''' this week.}}
# {{lb|en|euphemistic|hypocoristic}} The [[vulva]], especially the [[labia majora]].
#* {{RQ:Cleland Fanny Hill|I|106|{{...}} for ſtill, that my virgin-'''flower''' was yet uncrop'd never once enter'd into his head, and he would have thought it idling with time and words to have queſtion'd me upon it.}}
# The [[best]] examples or representatives of a group.
#* {{RQ:Skelton Complete|Scottes|116|lines=25–28|At {{w|Battle of Flodden|Floddon hyllys}},<br>Our bowys, our byllys<br>Slew all the '''floure'''<br>Of theyr honoure.}}
#* {{RQ:Hooker Laws}}
#*: The choice and '''flower''' of all things profitable the Psalms do more briefly contain.
#* {{RQ:Southey Cid}}
#*: the '''flower''' of the chivalry of all Spain
#* '''1915''', Katharine Tynan, ''The Golden Boy''
#*: In times of peace, so clean and bright, / And with a new-washed morning face, / He walked Pall Mall, a goodly sight, / The finished '''flower''' of all the race.
# The [[best]] state of things; the [[prime]].
#: {{ux|en|She was in the '''flower''' of her life.}}
#* {{RQ:Tennyson Clara}}
#*: A simple maiden in her '''flower''' / Is worth a hundred coats of arms.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[flour|Flour]].
#* {{RQ:Arbuthnot Aliments}}
#*: The '''Flowers''' of Grains, mixed with Water, will make a sort of Glue.
# {{senseid|en|sublimed powder}}{{lb|en|in the plural|chemistry|obsolete}} A substance in the form of a [[powder]], especially when [[condense]]d from [[sublimation]].
#* '''1661''', {{w|Robert Boyle}}, ''{{w|The Sceptical Chymist}}''
#*:Exposed to a moderate fire in subliming pots, [brimstone] rises all into dry, and almost tasteless, '''flower'''s; whereas being exposed to a naked fire, it affords store of a saline and fretting liquor.
#: {{ux|en|the '''flowers''' of sulphur}}
# A [[figure of speech]]; an [[ornament]] of [[style]].
# {{lb|en|printing}} Ornamental [[type]] used chiefly for borders around pages, cards, etc.
#* '''1841''', William Savage, ''A Dictionary of the Art of Printing''
#*:I pointed out to the late Mr. Catherwood, of the firm of Caslon and Catherwood, the inconvenience of both these modes of cutting '''flowers''',
# {{lb|en|in the plural|obsolete}} [[menstrual|Menstrual]] [[discharge]]s.
#* {{RQ:KJV|Leviticus|15|24||And if any man lye with her at all, and her '''flowers''' be vpon him, hee shall be vncleane seuen dayes: and all the bed whereon he lyeth, shall be vncleane.}}

=====Usage notes=====
In its most common sense as "a colorful conspicuous structure", the word ''flower'' includes many structures which are not anatomically flowers in the botanical sense. Sunflowers and daisies, for example, are structurally clusters of many small flowers that together appear to be a single flower (a {{m|en|capitulum}}, a form of {{m|en|pseudanthium}}), but these are considered to be ''flowers'' in the general sense. Likewise, the botanical definition of ''flower'' includes many structures that would not be considered a flower by the average person, such as the [[catkin]]s of a willow tree or the downy flowers found atop a [[cattail]] stalk.

